Sometimes the system is shut down in the incorrect order or an individual device is shut off independently. Tip Please do not shut anything off except for the items outlined in Shutting Down No Audio​ If there is no audio make sure each of the following devices are on and proceed to the Checking Audio Inputs section below Sound Board Switch on rear behind screen EQ Processor inside rack Power Switch on right side Just beneath Main Power Switch Speaker Amplifier Switch on right side Located at the bottom of the rack Sometimes these items get switched off Some pieces of equipment can be individually switched off. These Should Not but sometimes they do get switched off. If you are experiencing issues make sure that all items are on

The Extron Scan Converter to the right of the monitor will display numbers on the screen if the computer is outputting signal to the monitor and projector. If there is not a video signal it will read "No Signal". The Scan Converter converts the signal from the computer to analog video for the projector, it also provides the video signal to the monitor

Checking Audio Inputs​ The Channel Meters are located above each channels mute button. The Meters show visually the input level of the channel even if it is muted. The green level indicators should sit comfortably at the 12:00 position and should not take up the entire circle. If the meter shows too low or too high make an adjustment to the Gain setting according to the section below. Checking Audio Outputs​ Make sure the Master fader is set to U. If this slider is all the way down there's gonna be no sound. The output meter shows the audio levels on the output channels of the board Adjusting Audio Gain/Sensitivity​ Gain is the input sensitivity of an audio channel. Gain is adjusted with the knobs along the top of the console. OL - Overload Shows if a channels input is being overloaded and needs to be adjusted to a lower gain SIG - Signal Shows that a channel has a signal LINE Changes the input from a mic level input to a line level input. These should not be changed. 48V Enables 48 volt phantom power for Condenser microphones that require a 'bias voltage'. We do not use these mics regularly in this space and 48V should not be enabled. Take care Enabling 48V on sources not designed to accept phantom power like CD players, Keyboards, and other electronic sources can cause damage. Normal dynamic microphones will not be effected by this setting.

Docusaurus blogging features are powered by the blog plugin. Simply add Markdown files (or folders) to the blog directory. Regular blog authors can be added to authors.yml. The blog post date can be extracted from filenames, such as: 2019-05-30-welcome.md 2019-05-30-welcome/index.md A blog post folder can be convenient to co-locate blog post images: The blog supports tags as well! And if you don't want a blog: just delete this directory, and use blog: false in your Docusaurus config. Congratulations, you have made your first post! 2 Feel free to play around and edit this post as much you like.
Turn on the Computer with the button on the front. The computer desktop should show up on the monitor. Make sure it the display is switched on and has a Blue/Orange light showing on the right corner

Press the ON Button on the remote to turn the projector on. It will take a minute to warm up the lamp and display a picture. The correct input should already be selected. If there is no picture after a couple minutes check that the input is set to "Normal" Video Remote Inputs: "Normal" Video Video from the Grey Matrix selector "Desktop" RGB2 - Unused RGB1 - Unused

The Grey Matrix Switcher controls all inputs to the projector. To change sources select the desired Input on the top row, then select the Projector Output on the bottom row and press Enter on the right side. Matrix Inputs: Sanctuary - Input 1 Video from the broadcast system in the Sanctuary Computer - Input 2 Video from the fellowship hall computer. Duplicating the desktop for ease of use. DVD - Input 3 Signal from the DVD player to the right

Lets start by turning the system on. Find the Master Power Switch in the rack to the left of the computer. This switch controls all of the A/V systems in the Fellowship Hall and should be the only switch you need to interact with. info If you need the computer or projector visit The Computer and Projector article after the rest of the system is powered on. Take care Always shut down the computer before switching the system off Do not turn any switches off other than the Master Power Switch when you are finished with the space A detailed shutdown process is found on Shutting Down

When finished with the computer close out of all programs and Shut Down from the windows start menu. Take care ALways shut down the computer before switching the system off The Projector can be turned off either before or after the computer. Press the Standby button and confirm your selection by pressing it again, as the prompt on the projector screen shows.

To shut down the sound board and the rest of the system flip the Master Power Switch. Do Not Do Not switch anything off that is not outlined on this page.​ Turn off the lights on the right wall next to the kitchen if you are the last person in the space.

The sound board is the center of any presentation. Our sound board is no different. We have a number of different inputs pre-configured making it easy to find any source you're looking for. Each audio source in the Fellowship Hall has its own channel on the board. Channels 10-13 are configured for microphones. The mics are labeled with the channels they are connected to. The microphone for channel 13 is a handheld mic with a label of "Channel 13" on it Channels 18-24 are configured for the media devices in the sound booth. These are Line Level devices. External Audio from a phone or other external device plugged into the aux cord sitting on the table to the left of the sound board. DVD Input from the DVD Player DVD/Laptop Legacy input not in use currently Computer Audio from desktop computer Sanctuary Line input from the Sanctuary If There Is No Sound Make sure the Master fader is set to U. If this slider is all the way down there's gonna be no sound. If there is still no sound make sure the Speaker Amplifier is turned on. It is the device on the bottom of the rack under the Main Power If There Is No Power Visit Advanced and Troubleshooting Checking Inputs​ The Channel Meters are located above each channels mute button. The Meters show visually the input level of the channel even if it is muted. The green level indicators should sit comfortably at the 12:00 position and should not take up the entire circle.

The ATEM Video Switcher controls all video switching and processing. It receives all camera inputs, media inputs, and audio inputs and layers and combines them to create the stream. The 1 M/E indicates there is one Mix Effects bus available. The Mix Effects bus allows for a Digital Video Effect(DVE) to process the video. We use this DVE to position the lyrics and slides in the corner.

The Proton switcher control panel provides a physical control surface for the Video Switcher. There are a couple different sections to the controller. The Program (LIVE) display in the bottom corner allows the operator to check audio levels visually.
When the TV is configured for Preview the TV is used to check focus on a source before sending it to air, or taking it Live.

The ATEM Mini line of switchers has some additional features including audio processing and built in streaming. We use the audio compression and encoding features. The signal comes out of the larger ATEM switcher with embedded audio, the audio is processed by the Mini and then sent to youtube by the Mini. The only button that should need interacted with is the "On Air" button on the top right corner. The streaming is also triggered via automation at 2 different times to make sure the signal is being sent to youtube but should still be verified.

This section is a duplicate of Changing Video Sources via ATEM Software Control The ATEM video switcher is connected to the network and can be controlled via the Software Control application. There are tabs along the bottom for the Switcher, Media(Graphics), Camera, and Audio pages. The switcher page controls the same functions as the Proton control surface. The media page can be used to upload additional still graphics or change which are in the Media Player slots. Media Players Media Players are how the switcher can show or play its internal media. The QR code and offering banners can be show by pressing "DSK Auto" on the Proton. The QR code is ready to go ass soon as the computer loads the graphics, simple press "DSK1 Auto" to show and then hide it. To use the offering banner drag the image from the main Stills area in the center to Media Player 1 on the right side. After it is set as a media player select "DSK2 Auto" to overlay it.

Turn on rack power switch Turn on TV with button on bottom of screen In Chrome select todays livestream, it should be at the top of the list If the computer does not start, start it with the red button. Start encoding to youtube by pressing "On Air" on the top corner of the ATEM Mini device on top of the computer tower Hit "Go Live" in YouTube Studio 5 minutes before service Start with Graphic 1(Welcome Slide) until the Loop reaches the beginning on the Media Computer input(MC) Switch to MC for the Loop Auto/Cut transition to Camera 2 at beginning of service The Power Switch in the rack to the left controls power to the whole video streaming system. The TV on the right has power applied by the main power switch but still needs switched on usint the button on the bottom.
documents.s: Each item will be covered in more depth below but here is a list of tasks to get started and streaming.

documents.t: The computer should turn on with the rest of the system but if it does not press the red triangle button on the right side. As soon as the computer boots into windows it will automatically load graphics into the video switcher While graphics are loading Chrome will open into the youtube streaming homepage. You'll select the top item and continue to follow startup The next tab has a field of useful buttons. This tool is called Companion. The most helpful (currently) are the Encode, Recording, and Videohub:Loop/Videohub:Broadcast Feed buttons. These buttons provide feedback to confirm that the service is being recorded to the computer, streamed to YouTubes ingest servers, and wether the TVs are showing the loop or the produced feed from the streaming system. We use OBS to record our services and can also use it to stream to youtube if necessary. OBS is an acronym of Open Broadcaster Software and is a free application to record, composite, switch, and stream video on computers. OBS will show a symbol in the bottom right corner if a stream or recording is active as well as darkening the stream/record buttons on the right side. OBS is being triggered to start recording at 9:28, this automation serves a safety measure and should not be depended on without confirming that recording is active.

The ATEM video switcher is connected to the network and can be controlled via the Software Control application. There are tabs along the bottom for the Switcher, Media(Graphics), Camera, and Audio pages. The switcher page controls the same functions as the Proton control surface. The media page can be used to upload additional still graphics or change which are in the Media Player slots. Media Players Media Players are how the switcher can show or play its internal media. The QR code and offering banners can be show by pressing "DSK Auto" on the Proton. The QR code is ready to go ass soon as the computer loads the graphics, simple press "DSK1 Auto" to show and then hide it. To use the offering banner drag the image from the main Stills area in the center to Media Player 1 on the right side. After it is set as a media player select "DSK2 Auto" to overlay it.
documents.s: Changing Video Sources via ATEM Software Control

documents.t: The sound board is also connected to the network allowing for remote control of the Broadcast audio mix. After Universal Control is opened select the StudioLive 32 to open the main mix control. Do not make changes yet Make sure the Broadcast Mix is being controlled before changing any levels On the right side select Broadcast or Mix 11 to show the settings for audio being sent into the streaming system. After the mix is selected all the faders will change from white to green as shown in the pictures. Mics can be un-muted separately from the Main Mix if there isn't enough volume. Another benefit of this mix not being sent to speakers in the sanctuary is that as long as there is not feedback in the sanctuary these levels can be turned all the way up if necessary. The channels are blinking indicate that they are muted on the Main Mix. Mics can be muted/unmuted independently of the Main Mix but toggling the mute button
documents.s: Adjusting Mic Levels via Universal Control

documents.t: We have a trio of Lumens Pan-Tilt-Zoom cameras that allow one person to control all cameras without needing operators. The list of camera presets is on the wall above and will be further down in this page eventually. Recalling a camera position preset can be done by selecting the camera with F1, F2 or F3, selecting the desired preset and then pressing "Call". It is better looking if camera moves are not called while the camera is on air since the movements are not always very smooth. The selected camera will also show a red Tally light to indicate it is selected. A serial data connection could allow us to use the Tally outputs of the switcher to show which camera is currently live and which one is cued up in preview with red and green lights

The PTZ cameras are powered by Power-over-Ethernet and controlled via the network. PoE keeps the system a bit more simple by not needing power cables running everywhere. The cameras take about 30 seconds to boot before showing video signal
After the end of the service hit FTB on the switch and wait until the youtube preview goes black. After the preview goes black "End Stream" and stop the recording in OBS.

When finished with the computer close out of all programs and Shut Down from the windows start menu. Take care ALways shut down the computer before switching the system off After the computer is safely shut down you can flip the Main Power switch off. Turn off the lights and close the door when everything is finished.

The Videohub is used to route the different camera and video feeds around the FOH and through the building. Each camera is routed through the matrix so that we could use a camera as the video signal for the main and fellowship halls. We primarily switch between Input 1:Loop and Input 2:Broadcast Feed. The loop is shown before and after the services and the Broadcast Feed is used during the 9:30 and 11:00 services.
documents.s: The Videohub is a video routing matrix exactly like the previous one

documents.t: info A startup guide can be found at Starting to Stream
documents.s: An overview of all systems involved in the streaming

documents.t: The computer handles stream monitoring and control, recording, and remote audio control of the Broadcast Mix. The computer has its own page Here
The next device as we move to the right is the Camera Control Panel The camera control panel controls the PTZ(Pan Tilt Zoom) cameras along the balcony.

The next device as we move to the right is the Switcher Control Panel The Proton switcher control panel provides a physical control surface for the ATEM Video Switcher. It also has its own page. ATEM Switcher
Above the switcher control is the Multiview Monitor The multiview shows all sources connected to the switcher. Any of the video signals onscreen can be shown on the stream.
Finally to the right is a TV. This tv is used for checking focus on the preview signal or checking the status of the streaming encoder.
Moving under the desk the device on top is an ATEM Mini Pro switcher. This device is currently acting as the streaming encoder. It is processing the audio and sending the video stream to YouTube.
The power controller controls the main power to the system.

Now we are at the heart of the system. The ATEM Video Switcher controls all video switching and processing. It receives all camera inputs, media inputs, and audio inputs and layers and combines them to create the stream.

The last device in the rack is a network switch. This distributes network connectivity to all devices in the video system. It also powers all remote cameras. info Please shut down the computer before switching the system off A detailed shutdown process is found on Shutting Down
Let's discover Docusaurus in less than 5 minutes.
Get started by creating a new site. Or try Docusaurus immediately with docusaurus.new.
Node.js version 16.14 or above: When installing Node.js, you are recommended to check all checkboxes related to dependencies.

Generate a new Docusaurus site using the classic template. The classic template will automatically be added to your project after you run the command: npm init docusaurus@latest my-website classic You can type this command into Command Prompt, Powershell, Terminal, or any other integrated terminal of your code editor. The command also installs all necessary dependencies you need to run Docusaurus.

Run the development server: cd my-website npm run start The cd command changes the directory you're working with. In order to work with your newly created Docusaurus site, you'll need to navigate the terminal there. The npm run start command builds your website locally and serves it through a development server, ready for you to view at http://localhost:3000/. Open docs/intro.md (this page) and edit some lines: the site reloads automatically and displays your changes.

You have just learned the basics of Docusaurus and made some changes to the initial template. Docusaurus has much more to offer! Have 5 more minutes? Take a look at versioning and i18n. Anything unclear or buggy in this tutorial? Please report it!

Read the official documentation Modify your site configuration with docusaurus.config.js Add navbar and footer items with themeConfig Add a custom Design and Layout Add a search bar Find inspirations in the Docusaurus showcase Get involved in the Docusaurus Community
Docusaurus creates a page for each blog post, but also a blog index page, a tag system, an RSS feed...

Create a file at blog/2021-02-28-greetings.md: blog/2021-02-28-greetings.md --- slug: greetings title: Greetings! authors: - name: Joel Marcey title: Co-creator of Docusaurus 1 url: https://github.com/JoelMarcey image_url: https://github.com/JoelMarcey.png - name: Sébastien Lorber title: Docusaurus maintainer url: https://sebastienlorber.com image_url: https://github.com/slorber.png tags: [greetings] --- Congratulations, you have made your first post! Feel free to play around and edit this post as much you like. A new blog post is now available at http://localhost:3000/blog/greetings.
Add Markdown or React files to src/pages to create a standalone page: src/pages/index.js → localhost:3000/ src/pages/foo.md → localhost:3000/foo src/pages/foo/bar.js → localhost:3000/foo/bar

Create a file at src/pages/my-react-page.js: src/pages/my-react-page.js import React from 'react'; import Layout from '@theme/Layout'; export default function MyReactPage() { return (

My React page

This is a React page

 ); } A new page is now available at http://localhost:3000/my-react-page.
Create a file at src/pages/my-markdown-page.md: src/pages/my-markdown-page.md # My Markdown page This is a Markdown page A new page is now available at http://localhost:3000/my-markdown-page.
Docusaurus is a static-site-generator (also called Jamstack). It builds your site as simple static HTML, JavaScript and CSS files.
Build your site for production: npm run build The static files are generated in the build folder.

Test your production build locally: npm run serve The build folder is now served at http://localhost:3000/. You can now deploy the build folder almost anywhere easily, for free or very small cost (read the Deployment Guide).
Documents are groups of pages connected through: a sidebar previous/next navigation versioning
Create a Markdown file at docs/hello.md: docs/hello.md # Hello This is my **first Docusaurus document**! A new document is now available at http://localhost:3000/docs/hello.

Docusaurus automatically creates a sidebar from the docs folder. Add metadata to customize the sidebar label and position: docs/hello.md --- sidebar_label: 'Hi!' sidebar_position: 3 --- # Hello This is my **first Docusaurus document**! It is also possible to create your sidebar explicitly in sidebars.js: sidebars.js module.exports = { tutorialSidebar: [ 'intro', 'hello', { type: 'category', label: 'Tutorial', items: ['tutorial-basics/create-a-document'], }, ], };
Docusaurus supports Markdown and a few additional features.

Markdown documents have metadata at the top called Front Matter: my-doc.md --- id: my-doc-id title: My document title description: My document description slug: /my-custom-url --- ## Markdown heading Markdown text with [links](./hello.md)

Regular Markdown links are supported, using url paths or relative file paths. Let's see how to [Create a page](/create-a-page). Let's see how to [Create a page](./create-a-page.md). Result: Let's see how to Create a page.

Regular Markdown images are supported. You can use absolute paths to reference images in the static directory (static/img/docusaurus.png): ![Docusaurus logo](/img/docusaurus.png) You can reference images relative to the current file as well. This is particularly useful to colocate images close to the Markdown files using them: ![Docusaurus logo](./img/docusaurus.png)

Markdown code blocks are supported with Syntax highlighting. src/components/HelloDocusaurus.js function HelloDocusaurus() { return (

Hello, Docusaurus!

) } src/components/HelloDocusaurus.js function HelloDocusaurus() { return

Hello, Docusaurus!

; }

Docusaurus has a special syntax to create admonitions and callouts: My tip Use this awesome feature option ::: Take care This action is dangerous My tip Use this awesome feature option Take care This action is dangerous

MDX can make your documentation more interactive and allows using any React components inside Markdown: export const Highlight = ({children, color}) => ( { alert(`You clicked the color ${color} with label ${children}`) }}> {children} ); This is Docusaurus green ! This is Facebook blue ! This is Docusaurus green ! This is Facebook blue !
Let's translate docs/intro.md to French.
Modify docusaurus.config.js to add support for the fr locale: docusaurus.config.js module.exports = { i18n: { defaultLocale: 'en', locales: ['en', 'fr'], }, };

Copy the docs/intro.md file to the i18n/fr folder: mkdir -p i18n/fr/docusaurus-plugin-content-docs/current/ cp docs/intro.md i18n/fr/docusaurus-plugin-content-docs/current/intro.md Translate i18n/fr/docusaurus-plugin-content-docs/current/intro.md in French.

Start your site on the French locale: npm run start -- --locale fr Your localized site is accessible at http://localhost:3000/fr/ and the Getting Started page is translated. caution In development, you can only use one locale at a same time.

To navigate seamlessly across languages, add a locale dropdown. Modify the docusaurus.config.js file: docusaurus.config.js module.exports = { themeConfig: { navbar: { items: [ { type: 'localeDropdown', }, ], }, }, }; The locale dropdown now appears in your navbar:
Build your site for a specific locale: npm run build -- --locale fr Or build your site to include all the locales at once: npm run build
Docusaurus can manage multiple versions of your docs.

Release a version 1.0 of your project: npm run docusaurus docs:version 1.0 The docs folder is copied into versioned_docs/version-1.0 and versions.json is created. Your docs now have 2 versions: 1.0 at http://localhost:3000/docs/ for the version 1.0 docs current at http://localhost:3000/docs/next/ for the upcoming, unreleased docs

To navigate seamlessly across versions, add a version dropdown. Modify the docusaurus.config.js file: docusaurus.config.js module.exports = { themeConfig: { navbar: { items: [ { type: 'docsVersionDropdown', }, ], }, }, }; The docs version dropdown appears in your navbar:

It is possible to edit versioned docs in their respective folder: versioned_docs/version-1.0/hello.md updates http://localhost:3000/docs/hello docs/hello.md updates http://localhost:3000/docs/next/hello
